                <h2>READING PASSAGE 2: The Chronology of Written Script</h2>
                <p><strong>Paragraph A:</strong> The human drive to preserve acoustic speech via permanent graphic notation systems marked the true dawn of recorded history. Long before formalized characters were developed, prehistoric communities utilized primitive petroglyphs and geometric notches carved into ivory bones to track seasonal migrations or lunar intervals. These early markings functioned as proto-writing, lacking structural syntax but providing essential memory triggers for the community's survival rituals.</p>
                <p><strong>Paragraph B:</strong> The profound transition into fully standardized script materialized in Mesopotamia around 3200 BCE. The early Sumerian administrators faced immense challenges managing the logistical distribution of grain supplies and livestock trades within rapid municipal expansions. To resolve this bookkeeping crisis, accountants utilized sharp reeds to press wedge-shaped icons into soft clay tablets, initiating the writing system globally classified as cuneiform. This mechanical advancement transformed writing from abstract art into a tool for systemic administrative oversight.</p>
                <p><strong>Paragraph C:</strong> Independent of Middle Eastern advancements, ancient Mesoamerican civilizations engineered their own distinct linguistic notation frameworks. The Maya civilization created an incredibly complex hieroglyphic matrix composed of hundreds of individual glyphs representing complete syllables or absolute logograms. This script was reserved primarily for dynastic records, tracking the exact lineages of divine monarchs and calculating cosmic timelines across millions of years, reflecting a highly ritualistic function.</p>
                <p><strong>Paragraph D:</strong> This early scribal era was tightly monitored by exclusive academic elites. Because memorizing thousands of distinctive character variants required lifelong vocational training, scribes functioned as powerful political figures within imperial courts. Government agencies across Egypt and early China restricted the access to textual knowledge, ensuring that the general public remained illiterate, which naturally safeguarded the bureaucratic hierarchy from popular uprisings.</p>
                <p><strong>Paragraph E:</strong> By the second millennium BCE, the fundamental constraints of logographic scripts—where every single unique object required its own distinct symbol—precipitated a collapse in administrative efficiency. The maritime traders of Phoenicia, needing a fast, flexible framework to log seafaring commerce across the Mediterranean, abandoned complex images entirely. They developed a streamlined system consisting of just 22 abstract letters representing phonetic consonants, creating the world's first true linear alphabet.</p>
                <p><strong>Paragraph F:</strong> Technical infrastructural adjustments soon accelerated this linguistic democratization. In the second century CE, Chinese imperial court officials under Cai Lun pioneered the formulation of modern paper manufacturing using macerated mulberry bark and hemp fibers. This replacement of heavy bamboo strips or expensive silk sheets allowed textual materials to be produced cheaply and distributed extensively across vast geographical regions for the first time.</p>
                <p><strong>Paragraph G:</strong> The global consolidation of written literacy reached its climax in 15th-century Europe. Johannes Gutenberg's integration of movable metal type into a mechanical printing press initiated an unprecedented media revolution. Public interest in literary texts spiked dramatically, and traditional clerical hand-copying scripts were quickly obsolete. This industrialization shattered the monastic monopoly over knowledge production and paved the dynamic path for the European Renaissance.</p>
                <p><strong>Paragraph H:</strong> The evolution of writing demonstrates that script is not a fixed aesthetic ornament; rather, it adapts dynamically to the processing capacities of contemporary technical substrates, shifting from heavy stone tablets to digital pixels in an ongoing cycle of structural optimization.</p>
            </div>
